T1  - Quacks, Lemons, and Licensing: A Theory of Minimum Quality Standards
AU  - Leland, Hayne E.
Y1  - 1979/12/01
PY  - 1979
DA  - 1979/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260838
DO  - 10.1086/260838
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1328
EP  - 1346
VL  - 87
IS  - 6
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - I consider markets with asymmetric information. As suggested by Akerlof, quality deterioration in such markets may take place. I show that this is a general phenomenon. Minimum quality constraints (or "licensing requirements") are examined as a possible solution to the problem. Although not generally a first-best solution, such constraints will increase welfare in a number of cases. The types of markets that are likely to benefit from minimum quality standards are identified. It is then shown that, if quality standards are set by the profession (or industry) itself, it is likely that the standards will be too high.
